{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619021"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16527"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16527"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.04,0.04,0.37,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9218"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16527"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93980"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3233"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5940"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"},{"type":"tags","id":"10274"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45581"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUpper motor neurons in the cerebral cortex and brainstem provide descending control over spinal reflexes and resting muscle tone via multiple pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effects of upper motor neurons on spinal reflexes and resting muscle tone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases reflex sensitivity and increases muscle tone","Increases reflex sensitivity and decreases muscle tone","Has no effect on reflexes and decreases muscle tone","Decreases reflex sensitivity and decreases muscle tone","Decreases reflex sensitivity with no effect on muscle tone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases reflex sensitivity and increases muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because upper motor neurons exert a net facilitatory influence on spinal motor circuits, enhancing reflex responsiveness and contributing to baseline muscle tone through continuous descending input.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases reflex sensitivity and decreases muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E is inconsistent because modulation of reflexes and tone by upper motor pathways typically aligns in direction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHas no effect on reflexes and decreases muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as upper motor neurons actively modulate both reflex gain and tone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases reflex sensitivity and decreases muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E is the opposite of the normal net effect of upper motor neuron activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases reflex sensitivity with no effect on muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E ignores the essential role of descending pathways in maintaining tone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing loss of upper motor neuron input, there is often an initial phase of reduced reflexes and hypotonia, followed by hyperreflexia and spasticity as segmental circuits adapt to the absence of descending control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Upper motor neurons provide net facilitatory drive to spinal reflex circuits and help maintain resting muscle tone.","Loss of upper motor neuron input leads to reduced reflexes and tone acutely, then increased reflexes and spastic hypertonia chronically.","Descending pathways modulate both reflex sensitivity and baseline activity of alpha motor neurons."],"references":["Menon P, Vucic S. The Upper Motor Neuron-Improved Knowledge from ALS and Related Clinical Disorders. Brain Sci. 2021 Jul 21;11(8):958. doi: 10.3390/brainsci11080958. PMID: 34439577; PMCID: PMC8392624.","Emos MC, Agarwal S. Neuroanatomy, Upper Motor Neuron Lesion. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725990.","de Carvalho M, Swash M. Upper and lower motor neuron neurophysiology and motor control. Handb Clin Neurol. 2023;195:17-29. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-323-98818-6.00018-2. PMID: 37562869.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93980"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16527"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93980"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-21T14:42:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-21T14:42:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9218"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111916"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"t